    <h2>MIDI Routing Notes</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Hydrasynth Explorer MIDI DIN:</strong> connect MOTU MIDI Out → Hydrasynth MIDI In for DAW-sequenced control and clock sync. For standalone play, the Hydrasynth is its own MIDI controller via USB or DIN.</li>
      <li><strong>Yamaha P-225 DIN MIDI:</strong> MOTU MIDI Out → P-225 MIDI In for program-change and transport commands from Ableton when using the P-225 as a soft synth controller.</li>
      <li><strong>Launchkey 37 Mk3 Standalone:</strong> if the computer is off, use the Launchkey's MIDI Out (5-pin DIN) → Hydrasynth MIDI In for hardware-only performance.</li>
      <li><strong>MPE routing (Seaboard M):</strong> Seaboard M USB → computer → Ableton MIDI track input; set MIDI track to All Channels + MPE. Use the M4L MPE Control device if routing into a non-MPE instrument.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Audio Bus Structure in Ableton</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Vocal bus:</strong> SM58 (Ext. In 1) → Vocal Audio track → EQ Eight → Compressor → VT-3 Return (Ext. In 2 on a second track or Send/Return from the VT-3's Audio Out)</li>
      <li><strong>Synth bus:</strong> Hydrasynth (Ext. In 3/4) → Hydrasynth Audio track → sends to Reverb and Delay Return tracks</li>
      <li><strong>Piano bus:</strong> P-225 (Ext. In 5/6) → Piano Audio track (or MIDI track via External Instrument → instrument)</li>
      <li><strong>Master chain:</strong> all buses → Master track → Glue Compressor → EQ Eight (reference check) → out to MOTU Main Out 1/2 → HS7 monitors</li>
    </ul>

  </article>
